Related C++ code:
  - The functionality in this file corresponds to inline fixed-point arithmetic in:
    - src/emCore/emPainter.cpp lines 358-374 — uses 0x1000 (4096) scale, >>12 shifts, and 0xfff masks for sub-pixel AA coverage computation in PaintRect and scanline rasterization
    - src/emCore/emPainter_ScTl.cpp lines 296-326 — uses 0xFFF000 masks and >>24 shifts for scaled tile image coordinates (24-bit fixed point variant)
    - src/emCore/emPainter_ScTlIntImg.cpp lines 609-860 — extensive use of fixed-point for area sampling weights
  - Structural differences: C++ uses bare int variables with inline shifts/masks (e.g., `ix=(int)(x*0x1000); ix>>=12;`). Rust wraps these in a Fixed12 newtype with named methods. C++ has no dedicated fixed-point type; the 12-bit convention is implicit in variable naming (ix, iy, ax1, ax2, ay1, ay2). The Rust newtype makes the fractional-bit count explicit and prevents accidental mixing with plain i32 values.

OPEN QUESTIONS:
  - C++ also uses 24-bit fixed point in emPainter_ScTl*.cpp. Whether a Fixed24 type exists or is needed is not documented.

